Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1. Custom back button + confirmation dialog via `BackButtonBehavior`:**

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding GoBackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. ViewModel with unsaved-changes guard:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task GoBack()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave)
                return; // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**3. Intercept the hardware/Android back button** (the `BackButtonBehavior` command only handles the Shell toolbar button, not the device back button):

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
{
    var vm = BindingContext as EditProductViewModel;
    if (vm?.HasUnsavedChanges == true)
    {
        // Fire-and-forget the async dialog; return true to cancel navigation now
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // true = suppress default back navigation
    }

    return base.OnBackButtonPressed(); // no unsaved changes, navigate normally
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| Custom "Cancel" text | `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` |
| Toolbar back button intercept | `BackButtonBehavior.Command` |
| Device/hardware back button | `OnBackButtonPressed()` override |
| Cancel navigation | Return `true` from `OnBackButtonPressed`; skip `GoToAsync` in the command |

The two interception points are needed because `BackButtonBehavior.Command` doesn't fire for the Android hardware back button — `OnBackButtonPressed` covers that case.
